Creating Dataset¶

In [2]:
#join for each publisher files vocab i docword
files = pd.DataFrame([["data/docword.enron.csv","data/vocab.enron.txt"],
         ["data/docword.kos.csv","data/vocab.kos.txt"],
         ["data/docword.nips.csv","data/vocab.nips.txt"],
         ["data/docword.nytimes.csv", "data/vocab.nytimes.txt"]])
names = ["data/enron.csv", 'data/kos.csv', "data/nips.csv", "data/nytimes.csv"]
publishers = ["enron", "kos", "nips", "nytimes"]

for i in range(4):
    if i != 0:
        doc = pd.read_csv(files[0][i], skiprows = 4, index_col=None, header=None, names=['docId', 'wordId', 'count'], delimiter = ";")
    else:
        doc = pd.read_csv(files[0][i], skiprows = 4, index_col=None, header=None, names=['docId', 'wordId', 'count'])
    doc = doc.groupby(['wordId', "docId"])['count'].sum().reset_index()
    voc = pd.read_csv(files[1][i], index_col=None, header=None, names=['word'])
    voc['wordId'] = range(1, len(voc) + 1)
    pub = voc.merge(doc, on = 'wordId')
    pub = pub.drop(columns = ['wordId'])
    pub.columns = ["word","docId", "count"]
    pub["publisher"] = publishers[i]
    pub.to_csv(names[i], index = False)

# merge all publishers
data = pd.read_csv(names[0], index_col = None)
for i in range(3):
    data2 = pd.read_csv(names[i+1], index_col = None)
    maxId = max(data["docId"])
    data2["docId"] = data2["docId"] + maxId
    data = pd.concat([data, data2])

We will then reduce all words to their subject so that the same words in a different variety count as one. In order of that we will use two functions:

  • stemming
  • lammatization
In [20]:
def stemming(text):
    nltk_stemmList = []
    for word in text:
        nltk_stemmList.append(PorterStemmer().stem(word))
    return nltk_stemmList
In [21]:
def lemmatization(text):
    nltk_lemmaList = []
    for word in text:
        nltk_lemmaList.append(WordNetLemmatizer().lemmatize(word))
    return nltk_lemmaList

from sklearn.manifold import TSNE
from sklearn.metrics import davies_bouldin_score

def scatter(x, colors):
    palette = np.array(sns.color_palette("hls", 10))

    f = plt.figure(figsize=(16,16))
    ax = plt.subplot(aspect='equal')
    sc = ax.scatter(x[:,0], x[:,1], lw=0, s=40,
                    c=palette[colors.astype(np.int)])
    ax.axis('off')
    txts = []
    for i in range(10):
        # Position of each label.
        xtext, ytext = np.median(x[colors == i, :], axis=0)
        txt = ax.text(xtext, ytext, str(i), fontsize=24)
        txts.append(txt)

    return f, ax, sc, txts

    
def modeling(model,df):
    df2 = df
    try:
        model.fit(df2)
        label = model.predict(df2)
    except:
        label = model.fit_predict(df2)
    
        
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
    plt.scatter(x=df2[:,0], y=df2[:,1],label=label, c = label, cmap='viridis' )
    plt.show()
    
    label2 = model.fit_predict(df)
    print("davies_bouldin_score: " + str(davies_bouldin_score(df, label2)))

    
def modeling2(model,df):
    df2 = df
    try:
        model.fit(df2)
        label = model.predict(df2)
    except:
        label = model.fit_predict(df2)
    
        
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
    plt.scatter(x=df2[:,0], y=df2[:,1],label=label, c = label, cmap='viridis')
    plt.show()

Short summary of the early clustering¶

None of them achieved satisfactory results, so for each of them we will try to determine the number of clusters. We will try techniques listed below:

  • Elbow Method
  • Silhouette Coefficient
  • Calinski-Harabasz Index

Summary:¶

  • After combining all documents into one frame, we analyzed the data. In order to reduce the number of words in the frame that are written in an incorrect way we used the stemming and lammatization.
  • We removed all stopwords from the frame and all words that appear less than 10 times in the document.
  • The optimal number of components for pca for our frame is 800.
  • We decided to test the clustering results using 3 models: KMeans, Agglomerative Clustering, Birch.
  • The selection of the number of clusters was done with the help of methods: Elbow Method, Silhouette Coefficient, Calinski-Harabasz Index
  • We compared the clustering results using score.
  • The best score was obtained by the Birch model with davies_bouldin_score: 0.3112163639476151.
  • From the clustering results, the most optimal number of clusters will be 3 ( possibly 4).
